<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="chapter">
<PB N="407" REF="426">
<HEAD>CHAP. VIII.</HEAD>
<ARGUMENT>
<P>State of dome&s;tic affairs.&mdash;Steps towards a change.&mdash;Im|prudence of Godolphin and ob&s;tinacy of Marlborough.&mdash;Sunderland di&s;mi&s;&s;ed.&mdash;The allies interpo&s;e.&mdash;Leaders of the Whigs di&s;graced.&mdash;Character of the Earl of Whar|ton.&mdash;Marlborough offers his &s;ervice to the Pretender.&mdash;He receives a letter from the exiled Queen.&mdash;He applies to the hou&s;e of Hannover.&mdash;He accu&s;es Harley of Jaco|biti&s;m.&mdash;Unea&s;ine&s;s of the allies, and hopes of France.&mdash;Secret views of the court of St. Germains.&mdash;Godolphin's project for the Pretender.&mdash;His character.&mdash;A total change in the mini&s;try.&mdash;Intrigues of St. John and Har|court.&mdash;Whigs and Tories apply to Hannover.&mdash;New parliament.&mdash;Inquiry into mi&s;managements.&mdash;Coldne&s;s towards Marlborough.&mdash;Immen&s;e &s;upplies.&mdash;Harley &s;tab|bed.&mdash;He is made Earl of Oxford and lord-trea&s;urer.&mdash;Parallel between him and the Earl of Roche&s;ter.&mdash;Schemes of the Pretender.&mdash;He writes to Queen Anne.&mdash;Endea|vours to gain the mini&s;try.&mdash;Their profe&s;&s;ions to the fa|mily of Hannover.&mdash;Death of the Emperor.&mdash;Campaign of 1711.&mdash;In Flanders.&mdash;In Germany, Savoy, and Spain.&mdash;Naval affairs.&mdash;State and views of the hou&s;e of Bourbon.&mdash;And of the Briti&s;h mini&s;try.&mdash;Advances towards a peace.&mdash;A memorial from France.&mdash;Prelimi|naries of Great Britain.&mdash;Mr. Prior &s;ent to France.&mdash;Menager &s;ent privately to London.&mdash;Prior di&s;covered on his return.&mdash;The preliminaries become public.&mdash;Are de|fended by the mini&s;try.&mdash;They re&s;olve upon a peace.&mdash;Intrigues of Buys, the Dutch amba&s;&s;ador.&mdash;Elector of Hannover oppo&s;es the peace.&mdash;Intrigues of Bothmar.&mdash;Dangerous &s;chemes of the Whigs and confederates.&mdash;Marlborough's zeal for the Pretender.&mdash;Affair of the me|dal in Scotland.&mdash;A &s;e&s;&s;ion of parliament.&mdash;Intrigues of the allies and Whigs.&mdash;The lords declare again&s;t a peace.&mdash;Duke of Hamilton's patent rejected&mdash;Proceedings of the commons.&mdash;Di&s;grace of the Duke of Marlborough.&mdash;Cau&s;e of that mea&s;ure.&mdash;Ob&s;ervations on his character and conduct.&mdash;Reflections.</P>
